# A person who gives an [[address]] or [[speech]].
#* '''1916''', {{w|Stella Benson}}, ''I Pose'', Chapter I, pp. 305-306,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/ipose00bens]</sup>
#*: The girls were listening with the polite though precarious attention which Brown Borough girls always bring to bear on the first three hundred words of any address, especially if the '''addresser''' be a man.
# A person who addresses someone (directs spoken or written communication toward someone).
#* '''1788''', {{w|Hannah Cowley}}, ''The Fate of Sparta'', London: G.G.J. and J. Robinson, dedicatory letter,<sup>[http://name.umdl.umich.edu/004803506.0001.000]</sup>
#*: When letters were in their infancy, and when knowledge and the arts were groping their way through seemingly impervious mists, some splendid name was necessary to give an author celebrity—hence the custom of <small>DEDICATIONS</small>; hence those floods of adulation, which poured from the press, and outraged the feelings of the '''addresser''' and the addressed.
#* '''1969''', {{w|Maya Angelou}}, ''{{w|I Know Why the Caged Bird Sings}}'', New York: Bantam, 1971, Chapter 5, p. 22,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/iknowwhycagedbi000maya]</sup>
#*: All adults had to be addressed as Mister, Missus, Miss, Auntie, Cousin, Unk, Uncle, Buhbah, Sister, Brother and a thousand other appellations indicating familial relationship and the lowliness of the '''addressor'''.
# A person who addresses (applies an address to an object to be delivered to a particular location).
#* '''1906''', {{w|G. K. Chesterton}}, ''{{w|Charles Dickens}}: A Critical Study}}'', New York: Dodd Mead & Co., Chapter 2, p. 25,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/charlesdickenscr01ches]</sup>
#*: {{...}} if they had not been lifted in the air by the enormous accident of a man of genius, the Dickenses, I fancy, would have appeared in poorer and poorer places, as inventory clerks, as caretakers, as '''addressers''' of envelopes, until they melted into the masses of the poor.
# A machine that addresses.

